     =20





 =20
 =20

 =20
 =20

 =20
           =20
 =20

  <p>Scientists measure radiation in different ways. Sometimes, they measur=
e the dose that a person receives from a radioactive source, and sometimes =
they measure the amount of radioactivity in water, or in soil, or in the ai=
r. These measurements are taken to determine if safety actions are needed.&=
nbsp;</p>

<p>There are different but interrelated units for measuring radioactivity a=
nd estimating health effects.</p>

<p><strong>On this page:</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.epa.gov/radiation/radiation-terms-and-units#rad=
ioactivity">Radioactivity</a></li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.epa.gov/radiation/radiation-terms-and-units#abs=
orbed-dose">Absorbed Dose</a></li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.epa.gov/radiation/radiation-terms-and-units#eff=
ective-dose">Effective Dose</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>


<p><a id=3D"radioactivity" name=3D"radioactivity" data-once=3D"external-lin=
ks protected-links"></a></p>



