  <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>A dose to the lens of the eyes from a brain CT scan is about 60 millig=
ray (mGy) or 6 rad.</li>
	<li>A dose to the thyroid from a chest CT scan is about 10 milligray (mGy)=
 or 1 rad.<sup>3</sup></li>
</ul>

<h3 id=3D"dialog-title">Unit Conversions and Calculations</h3>

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th>Topic</th>
			<th>
			<p>Gray (Gy) | International or SI unit</p>
			</th>
			<th>
			<p>Rad (rad) | U.S. unit</p>
			</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td><strong>How the unit is derived</strong></td>
			<td>
			<p>Absorbed dose is energy per unit mass</p>

			<p>1 gray (Gy) =3D 1 joule(J)/kilogram(kg)</p>
			</td>
			<td>1 rad =3D 0.01 joule(J)/kilogram(kg)</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><strong>Conversions</strong></td>
			<td>1&nbsp;gray (Gy)&nbsp;=3D 100 rad&nbsp;</td>
			<td>1 rad =3D 0.01 gray (Gy)</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><strong>Common Metric Prefixes</strong></td>
			<td>
			<p>1 centigray (cGy) =3D 0.01 Gy</p>

			<p>1 milligray&nbsp;(mGy) =3D 0.001 Gy&nbsp;</p>
			</td>
			<td>
			<p>1 millirad (mrad) =3D 0.001&nbsp;rad</p>

			<p>1 kilorad (krad) =3D 1,000 rad&nbsp;</p>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

